<!-- 01 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01 · What we do</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Display cases are commercial refrigeration's most demanding category.</h2>

    <p>Display cases are customer-facing. Glass doors must stay clear of fog, lighting must be flattering, temperature must hold without visible condensation, and the whole unit must look pristine while running 24/7 in retail environments. When a deli case fogs, customers walk past. When a bakery case ices over, the pastries ship to the trash.</p>

    <p>Our techs service display cases across LA, Orange, Ventura, San Bernardino, Riverside. Two architectures: <strong>self-contained</strong> (compressor and condenser inside the case, typical for grocery aisle merchandisers, smaller deli cases, single-unit bakery displays) and <strong>remote-condensed</strong> (compressor and condenser mounted on the roof or in a back room, refrigerant lines run to the case, typical for larger restaurant deli setups, multi-case grocery installations).</p>

    <p>Most appliance shops decline remote-condensed display cases because the line set work and roof access fall outside their training. We service both. EPA 608 Universal certified. BHGS #A49573. BBB A+. Phones answered 24/7. Parent context: <a href="/commercial/refrigeration/">commercial refrigeration repair</a>.</p>

    <p>Common brands we see: <strong>Hussmann</strong> (Panasonic-owned, dominant in LA grocery), <strong>Federal Industries</strong> (Wisconsin, dominant in deli and bakery cases), <strong>True TG-Series</strong> (Trulaske family), <strong>Howard McCray</strong> (Pennsylvania, premium deli and bakery), <strong>Beverage-Air</strong> (Ali Group, retail merchandisers), <strong>Hoshizaki Display</strong> (premium Japanese).</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 TYPICAL FAILURES -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">02 · Typical display case failures</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Ten failure modes account for nearly every display case service call.</h2>

    <ol class="num-list">
      <li><strong>Glass-frame anti-condensation heater wire failure (year 5 to 8).</strong> The most common display case failure. Heater wire embedded in the door frame fails (open-circuit), glass front fogs, customers can't see product. Replacement requires partial frame disassembly. $340 to $620.</li>
      <li><strong>Internal humidity control issues.</strong> Defrost cycle imbalance causes excess moisture inside the case. Food sweats, presentation degrades. Diagnostic of defrost timing plus airflow patterns.</li>
      <li><strong>Condenser fan motor (self-contained units).</strong> Same as reach-ins, 4 to 6 year coastal life. $280 to $500.</li>
      <li><strong>Evaporator fan motor.</strong> Circulates cold air through case interior. $260 to $450.</li>
      <li><strong>LED lighting harness corrosion.</strong> Display lighting harness fails at humid corners. Critical because customer-facing aesthetic. $260 to $480.</li>
      <li><strong>Door gasket compression.</strong> Heavy customer-facing door cycling (200+ per day on grocery displays). $200 to $380 per door.</li>
      <li><strong>Defrost timer or control board.</strong> Modern displays use defrost boards, legacy use timers. $300 to $580.</li>
      <li><strong>Refrigerant leak (remote-condensed).</strong> Line set leaks at brazed joints. EPA 608 leak repair before recharge. $700 to $1,500.</li>
      <li><strong>Sliding door track corrosion.</strong> Sliding-door variants on bakery and deli, track replacement, customer-facing aesthetic critical.</li>
      <li><strong>Glass-edge desiccant breach.</strong> Glass-panel desiccant fails, double-pane glass develops permanent fog. Replacement glass panel.</li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 ARCHITECTURE -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">03 · Two architectures, different repair playbooks</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Self-contained vs remote-condensed.</h2>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Self-contained displays</h3>
    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li>Compressor plus condenser inside the case body</li>
      <li>Heat rejected from back or bottom of unit into the room</li>
      <li>Easier service access (everything in one place)</li>
      <li>Limited cooling capacity (smaller compressor)</li>
      <li>Most deli grab-and-go cases, small bakery cases, beverage merchandisers</li>
      <li>Service brands: Federal Industries small cases, True TG-Series, Beverage-Air merchandisers</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Remote-condensed displays</h3>
    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li>Compressor plus condensing unit mounted on roof OR in back room</li>
      <li>Refrigerant line set runs from condensing unit to case</li>
      <li>Much higher cooling capacity (larger compressor)</li>
      <li>Heat rejected outside the building (no room load)</li>
      <li>Most grocery store multi-case banks, large restaurant deli setups</li>
      <li>Service brands: Hussmann (most LA grocery), Howard McCray premium, Federal Industries large cases</li>
      <li><strong>Many appliance shops won't service these.</strong> They require line set work, sometimes roof access, knowledge of pre-charged systems vs field-charged. We do them.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 04 REAL STORIES -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">04 · Recent jobs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Real repair stories from the last few weeks.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Composite examples; model numbers, ages, and prices are accurate to typical scope.</p>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>Beverly Hills · Federal Industries deli case 8' SN8 series, 11 years old, R-134a self-contained</h3>
      <p>Bakery. Glass front fogging. Diagnosed: anti-condensation heater wire open-circuit at lower-left corner of glass frame. 5-day part order from Federal Industries. Returned, partial frame disassembly, replaced heater wire, tested defrost-condensation cycle through 24 hours. Total: $120 plus $385 part plus 2.5 hours across 2 visits = $720.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>Pasadena · Hussmann RLN remote-condensed multi-case bank, 9 years old</h3>
      <p>Grocery store. Case 3 of 5 not holding temp. Diagnosed: refrigerant leak at line set joint near the case (between condenser and evap). EPA 608 leak repair: pumped down, brazed line repair, vacuum to 500 microns, recharged R-404A. Coordinated with grocery operations to minimize stocked inventory disruption. Total: $120 plus $620 refrigerant plus $880 labor plus leak detection = $1,820. Insurance documentation provided.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>West Hollywood · True TG-2 two-section glass-door merchandiser, 7 years old, R-290</h3>
      <p>Deli. Temp climbing in left section. Diagnosed: condenser fan motor seized (self-contained unit, 7 years). Replaced motor (True OEM). R-290 system requires R-290 certification, we have it. Pulldown to 38°F. Total: $120 plus $295 part plus 1 hour = $480.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>Santa Monica · Howard McCray dual-zone dessert display, 6 years old</h3>
      <p>Restaurant kitchen plus dining-room display. Internal humidity high, desserts sweating. Diagnosed: defrost cycle running too long (timer drift) plus internal fan recirculating moisture. Adjusted defrost timer, replaced internal recirculation fan. Total: $120 plus $385 plus 2 hours = $750.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>Marina del Rey · Beverage-Air vertical merchandiser MMR49, 5 years old</h3>
      <p>Coffee shop. LED lighting flickering on right side. Diagnosed: LED harness corrosion at lower right (coastal moisture). Replaced harness section. Total: $120 plus $310 part plus 1 hour = $510.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 05 HONEST SCOPE -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">05 · Honest scope</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What we do, and what we don't.</h2>

    <p><strong>We service:</strong></p>
    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li>Self-contained display cases (all sizes, all brands listed)</li>
      <li>Remote-condensed display cases (line set work, roof access, multi-case banks)</li>
      <li>Glass-frame anti-condensation heater service</li>
      <li>Defrost cycle diagnosis and adjustment</li>
      <li>LED lighting harness replacement (when refrigeration-integrated)</li>
      <li>All EPA-permitted refrigerants (R-22, R-134a, R-404A, R-448A, R-449A, R-290, R-454B)</li>
      <li>Hussmann, Federal Industries, True TG, Howard McCray, Beverage-Air, Hoshizaki Display</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>We don't do:</strong></p>
    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li>New display case installation (specialty installer trade)</li>
      <li>Remote-condensed condenser unit roof installation (HVAC C-20 contractor)</li>
      <li>Multi-case grocery rack systems with multiplexed condensers (specialty C-38 contractor)</li>
      <li>Stand-alone aesthetic glass replacement (specialty glass trade, though we coordinate)</li>
      <li>Display lighting that's purely electrical (not refrigeration-integrated)</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Knowing the boundary is part of being a real practitioner. Premium retail and restaurant operators value contractors who refer specialty work to specialists rather than fake competence.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 06 PRICING -->
<section class="section section-gray">
